Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. comment on the roles of biomolecules in the human body through their participation in different metabolic pathways;
2. describe the metabolic pathways of carbohydrate, protein, lipid, and nucleic acids in detail, and discuss the ways that the metabolisms are connected;
3. illustrate the mechanisms of gene regulations in prokaryotes and eukaryotes; discuss the impact of mutations in generating different genetic diseases including those associated with metabolic disorders;
4. through topical studies and preparing a presentation, discuss how modern medicine revolutionizes our understanding of metabolism, diseases, and their impact on our daily lives.

After completion of the course, students should be able to:
a) explain the functions of the cells and basic tissues;
b) describe the basic anatomical features of the musculoskeletal, cardiovascular, autonomic nervous, immune, respiratory and digestive systems;
c) recall the basic physiological functions of the musculoskeletal, cardiovascular, autonomic nervous, immune, respiratory and digestive system; and
d) apply their anatomical and physiological knowledge to explain the abnormal conditions of diseases found in these body systems.

